1. Introduction¶

In recent years, there has been a huge amount of convolutional neural network structures come out for semantic segmentation tasks. The most famous of these is AlexNet, proposed by Alex Krizhevsky in 2012 on the ILSVRC competition, which opened the door to the application of deep convolutional neural networks on GPU and beat all traditional algorithms.

This assignment comes from the 2017 Automated Cardiac Diagnosis Challenge (ACDC). We will be designing a convolutional neural network to segment the CMR images into four distinct regions(the background region (black), the left ventricle (LV) region (white), the myocardium (Myo) region (white gray) and the right ventricle (RV) region (dark gray).) as accurately and reliably as possible, to reduce the time-consuming, labour-intensive and poor quality of manual segmentation.

The dataset provided to us was split in advance into training, validation and test. For the training set, there are 100 CMR images and 100 respective ground truth mask images. We will use these to train our model. For the validation set, there are 20 CMR images and 20 mask images, we will use the set to tune the hyperparameters of our networks. For the test set, we will use it for kaggle submission to prove that our model is valid.

We want our convolutional neural network to be able to appropriately segment the test data to the four regions to a high accuracy. We want our network to avoid underfitting and overfitting, instead producing a reasonable mask of any given image. In order for us to achieve this we will be focusing on finding the optimum network architecture and loss function for image segmentation. Furthermore, by using optimisers and augmenting the dataset we aim to increase the accuracy and reliability of the segmentation.

2. Implementation¶

2.1 Preprocessing - Data Augmentation¶

We augmented the data by using numpy to flip our data set (fliplr() and flipud()) and rotated the data anti-clockwise in steps of 90 degrees (rot90()) three times to increase the size of the dataset from 100 images to 600.This increase in variety in our data will decrease the risk of the network remembering the training data andhelp prevent a large difference in segmentation performance from training to validation in the network.

2.2 Segmentation Model - FCN¶

The idea of FCN is based on CNN. It replaced the fully connected layer of CNN by fully convolutional layer and it can classify images at the pixel level. Therefore, it solved the semantic segmentation of image segmentation. Finally, the loss of SoftMax classification is calculated pixel by pixel, which is equivalent to one training label for each pixel. Overall, FCN replaces the fully connected layer at the end of CNN with the convolutional layer, and the output an image which is already labeled.

VGG-16 Structure

In our FCN, we first use the VGG16 convolutional part as FCN convolutional part. In original VGG16, the image input size is 224*224*3 and the max channels are 512. For each convolutional layer, only the number of channels is changed, and the size is become one half after each maxpool layer, which means after 5 convolutional layers, the size becomes 1/8 of its original size. However, this structure might not work well on this dataset, as the magnetic resonance (MR) dataset is 96*96*1. It is necessary to adapt the layers and parameters to fit our dataset. We keep each convolutional layer parameter as same as VGG16 except the input and output channel. The input channel for first layer which is input layer is obviously 1 and the output channel becomes 16. The output channel of rest four convolutional layers is 32, 64, 128, 256 respectively. That’s all of the convolutional part. An advantage of this structure is when doing convolutional part to extract the features, the size never changed and it means information that is not lost at the edge of the image. And the maxpool layer reduce the size of feature map and improve the anti-interference ability of network.

VGG16-FCN Structure

Then the upsample part aims to make the convolved image return to the input size. The easiest way to implement this is to use upsampling at a factor of 32. However, as we can see on figure2 the predicted mask, it is generally similar with origin mask, the details are very poor. In addition, the accuracy of validation in this case is only around 70%.

Unsampling as factor of 32

Therefore, we use upsampling at a factor of 2 first, apply this to the output of convolutional layer, and add with the output of fourth convolutional part, we get “x1”. Using “x1” and add with the output of third convolutional part, we get “x2”. Finally, using “x2” with upsampling at a factor of 8, we get the predicted output. Now, the predicted mask as shown on figure 3, most of the details are fine, and we can reach the maximum validation accuracy about 88%.

Upsampling as factor of 2,2,8

In summary, there are 5 convolutional part and 3 upsample part in our VGG16-FCN network. The output shape of each convolutional part after maxpool are 48*48*16, 24*24*32, 12*12*64, 6*6*128, 3*3*256. Total parameters in this network are 2,578,292 and total storage is about 25.76MB.

2.3 Segmentation Model - DeepLab v3 plus¶

Besides the network we implement with FCN and VGG-16, we also explore many other network architectures. The Deeplab series is the most interesting to us, and we have chosen the latest one to perform semantic segmentation on our task. The state-of-art network Deeplab v3 plus was proposed in 2018 by Google and has been open-sourced on TensorFlow, which combines the advantages of various networks of recent years.

Deeplab v3 plus network

As seen in the image above, the network uses the Encoder-Decoder framework which was used before such as network U-Net. The encoder part gradually reduces spatial dimensionality, while the decoder gradually restores spatial dimensionality by using bilinear upsampling with low-level features to detail the information.

For the encoder part, the DCNN module of v3 plus using the Aligned Xception.

In the entry flow, the image goes through three blocks. What they have in common is that they are all roughly downsampled with a 1x1 filter by a factor of two and increased channels, then it added with the feature map after 3 rounds of 3x3 filter depthwise separable convolution. In the last layer of the last entry flow block, a atrous convolution with rate 2 is used at the end to preserve field of view. The final feature map output size of entry flow is 6*6.

In the middle flow, it is repeated 16 times with 3 convolutional layers of 3x3 filter without changing the size and channels to get detail features further.

In the last exit flow, the first block has the same functionality of the blocks in the entry flow, the last layer of it does the last atrous convolution with rate 4 and then using 3 depthwise convolutional layers increase only the channels of feature map, without changing the size of it.

Then ASPP module after the DCNN was used to extract of feature maps of different sizes for final concatenation.

For the decoder part, the decoder first reduces channels of low-level feature map produced during the second block of the entry flow of the encoder with a 1x1 filter convolutional layer, then concatenates the output of the encoder which was after bilinear 4x upsampling, then use two 3x3 filters convolutional layer and one 1x1 filter convolutional layer before the final bilinear 4x upsampling, and then upsampling 4x to get the final mask with size and channels of [4,4,96,96].

After implementing the network structures, we try to train the model with our data set. We didn’t make much changes to the network initially, and we were able to train the model with our own data augmentation training set to achieve 84-92% accuracy, but the validation set only achieved 62-70% accuracy. This is a sign of overfitting.

So, we did the same thing we did for VGG-16, by changing the channels of each layers inside of the network, in addtion, we add dropout inside to avoid overfitting. We keep the output stride to be 16 rather than 32, which means the output feature map of encoder will be the size of 6*6 (height and width reduced by 16 times compared to the original image size 96*96).

The best result then we get from the validation set is 88%, but it only reachs 85% on Kaggle for the test set.

In summary, the DeepLab series has been one of the most important semantic segmentation networks to date.It started with an atrous convolution and gradually added more features from other networks, such as SPP and Decoder, to make it even stronger.

2.4 Loss functions¶

We first considered 3 loss functions: Cross Entropy Loss, Negative log-likelihood (NLL) loss and Soft dice loss. Cross entropy and Negative log-likelihood already have implementations in Torch.nn (CrossEntropyLoss() and NLLLoss2d()) so we used those. However, we had to implement Soft Dice loss ourselves. The class follows the general structure of a Torch.nn module, with the only argument being an optional smoothing factor. The forward function implements the process of finding soft dice loss. The shape of the input is found and appropriate axes created, and then the true positives, false positives and false negatives are returned by the helper function get_results(). These are used to calculate the Dice Coefficient (dc), which is negated and returned as the loss value. Soft dice does however have drawbacks – it is vulnerable to overfitting and bias from unbalanced datasets. It is important to consider this in any segmentation problem, as I hypothesise that the background class may be unbalanced compared to the rest of the dataset.

However, individual loss functions have weaknesses; these weaknesses can be bridged by considering several loss functions in conjunction. We implemented such a function, “CrossDice”. This is a basic combination of Soft dice loss and Cross entropy loss. In this function the individual loss values are calculated, before they are multiplied to produce an overall loss value. I expect this function to perform better than the standard soft dice implementation, as it will accommodate for the weaknesses in bias and overfitting by introducing Cross Entropy loss into the function.

3.1.2 Exploration of Deeplab v3 plus¶

Significantly reducing the number of operations in a neural network is still one of the goals of network structure optimization due to the hardware constraints of the device.

Before improvement, the DCNN part of Deeplab v3 plus was using original backbone as suggested in the original paper which was ResNet-101 using the complete convolution like the v3 version, google later released the new suggestion on tensorflow by using depthwise separable convolution in the new backbone --> Aligned Xception(a fine tune version of the Xception network). As you can see it above, we use the new suggestion to solve the former network being very computationally intensive and demanding of hardware.

We do some math to understand the benefits of doing so. The core idea is to decompose a complete convolutional operation into two steps, Depthwise Convolution and Pointwise Convolution.

Assuming that the input layer is a 3-channel colour image of size 64x64, and that it passes through a convolution layer with 4 filters, the final output is 4 feature maps, each of the filter size is 3 × 3. The number of parameters used in a regular convolution operation is 4 × 3 × 3 × 3 = 108.

If a Depthwise separable convolution is used, the first convolution is performed in a two-dimensional plane, and the number of filters is the same as the depth of the previous layer. The number of parameters in depthwise convolution part is 3 × 3 × 3 = 27. This does not make effective use of the information from different maps at the same spatial location. So the Pointwise Convolution operation (1×1×Depth) will combine the maps from the previous step in a weighted manner in the depth direction to generate a new Feature map. The number of parameters in pointwise convolution part is 1 × 1 × 3 × 4 = 12.

Total parameters: 27 + 12 = 39

The number of parameters for depthwise separable convolution is about 1/3 of the number for the complete convolution.

3.2 Loss Function¶

The first consideration regarding loss functions is which one to use. To ascertain if there was a frontrunner, we first tested each loss function on a basic model with only a subset of the data over 50 epochs. This experiment did not show one function as a clear frontrunner, but rather showed one as clearly less appropriate than the others. A table of results can be seen below.

As can be seen in the above table, Soft Dice loss performs considerably worse than the other approaches, so a purely Soft Dice loss function was deemed to be inappropriate for this task. Although some approaches do slightly better than others, it would be unwise to draw any such conclusions between these approaches as this was only tested on a small subset of the data.

Despite performing well on the more simple models, Cross Dice and NLL losses struggled with more comprehensive models or larger datasets/more training epochs. In validation, these approaches could only achieve an average accuracy of around 0.85, whereas Cross Entropy loss achieved around 0.89 in validation. I believe this is largely an issue of overfitting and a lack of stability in the approaches, as the training accuracy was still sound despite the instability in loss which ultimately yielded poor results when run on the unseen validation data.

There are few parameters to be varied in loss functions. In Cross Entropy loss, the only parameter to be varied is applying weights to the different classes to lessen the impact of an unbalanced dataset. The default weight of a class is 1, such that a weight of 0.5 will halve the impact of the given class. In this task there are 4 classes representing different areas of the mask, and intuitively the background is much more significant than the rest of the image. To test this hypothesis, we first ran 4 test configurations where one weight was set to 0.5 and the rest left as 1. The model was only trained for 20 epochs on a subset of the data for efficiency. The results of this test are shown in the table below

As can be seen above, a lesser weighting for Class 1 produces far better results then the other tests performed, whilst weighting the other classes does not exhibit a significant improvement on accuracy. Because of this, we chose to use Cross Entropy loss with a reduced weighting for Class 1. It follows intuitively that reducing the weights of several classes will reduce the impact of the other reductions, so it is important to limit the number of weight reductions that take place. Therefore, as there are only 4 classes in this example we chose to only reduce the weight of the most optimal class, which is class 1.

4. Conclusion¶

The size of the input images in the semantic segmentation task affects the overall performance of each network, and fine tuning of the network structure is important. In the FCN network structure, the best performance is achieved by using 3x3 kernel size with 1 padding and 1 stride. After each five convolutional blocks, there is a batch normalization layer to avoid overfitting and maxpool layer to extract the features. And the output size of each blocks are (4,1,96,96), (4,16,48,48), (4,32,24,24), (4,128,6,6) and (4,256,3,3). And upsampling layer is used after convolutional part is finished. And to make the prediction more accuracy, we use 2x, 2x, and 8x as upsampling factor instead of 32x directly. Because it adds the feature maps which is the output of 3rd and 4th convolutional part. Finally, with the best loss function Adam with 0.01 learning and best optimizer which is found by other group member, we obtain over 0.93 accuracy for training, over 0.88 accuracy for validation. And for test set, we submitted to Kaggle, it achieved 0.88431, and it’s the best accuracy in these 2 models we implemented.

In the deeplab v3 plus network, we found that there are three key enhancements that are important. Due to the large amount of network parameters computed, the use of depth separable convolution becomes critical, using the new backbone to do a perfect illustration of this. Secondly, ASPP was retained to increase speed while increasing the field of view with enhanced perception of different sizes of the same object. The Encoder-Decoder framework incrementally recovers features from the feature map rather than directly up-sampling or accessing the fully-connected layer, which also improves accuracy and efficiency. Lastly, adjusting the number of channels between the layers of the network and adding dropout to prevent overfitting are necessary to achieve high accuracy as usual.

We tried several loss functions, but ultimately the relatively simple Cross Entropy loss was the most effective. We believe this is down to overfitting caused by the more complex Soft Dice loss and the combined “Cross Dice” function. From the related literature we know that Cross Entropy is a robust metric which is often the most effective loss function for image segmentation problems, so it was expected that this function would perform well in this problem. The weighting for each class was also similar to what we hypothesised, where the background would cause the dataset to be somewhat unbalanced so should be given a lesser weight compared to the rest of the classes. This increased performance on the validation set compared to an unweighted set.

For the optimizer, each algorithm doesn’t have a large difference between them, the performance is quite well. We choose currently the most popular one – Adam as our optimizer. It is an alternative stochastic gradient descent optimization algorithm for training deep learning models, and it combines the best features of the AdaGrad and RMSProp algorithms to provide an optimization algorithm that can deal with sparse gradients on noise problems. In addition, Adam’s memory requirement is low and suitable for a large and high dimension dataset, especially image problem.

Overall, after extensive tuning and experimentation, our FCN network achieved a final test set accuracy of 88.4%, while the more complex Deeplab achieved a maximum test set accuracy of 85.2% in this task, despite many structural improvements.

2. Preprocessing - Data Augmentation¶

The original training set is 100 images, which is not enough and may cause the overfitting. Therefore, we applied Data Augmentation to generate more training data.

We applied:

  • Flip from left to right
  • Flip from up to down
  • Rotate 90°
  • Rotate 180°
  • Rotate 270°

Now we have 600 images and masks for training

In [3]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import cv2
import os

input_dir = './data/train'
output_dir = './new_data/train'
files = ['image', 'mask']

for file_name in files:
    input_path = os.path.join(input_dir, file_name)
    output_path = os.path.join(output_dir, file_name)
    for img_name in os.listdir(input_path):
        image = cv2.imread(os.path.join(input_path, img_name), cv2.IMREAD_UNCHANGED)

        #Flip from left to right
        flippedlr_img = np.fliplr(image)
        cv2.imwrite(os.path.join(output_path, img_name), image)
        cv2.imwrite((output_path + '/flipped_' + img_name), flippedlr_img)
        
        #Flip from up to down
        flippedud_img = np.flipud(image)
        cv2.imwrite(os.path.join(output_path, img_name), image)
        cv2.imwrite((output_path + '/flippedud_' + img_name), flippedud_img)
        
        #Rotate 90°
        rotated90_img = np.rot90(image)
        cv2.imwrite(os.path.join(output_path, img_name), image)
        cv2.imwrite((output_path + '/rotated90_' + img_name), rotated90_img)
        
        #Rotate 180°
        rotated180_img = np.rot90(rotated90_img)
        cv2.imwrite(os.path.join(output_path, img_name), image)
        cv2.imwrite((output_path + '/rotated180_' + img_name), rotated180_img)
        
        #Rotate 270°
        rotated270_img = np.rot90(rotated180_img)
        cv2.imwrite(os.path.join(output_path, img_name), image)
        cv2.imwrite((output_path + '/rotated270_' + img_name), rotated270_img)

import torch
import torch.utils.data as data
import cv2
import os
from glob import glob

class TrainDataset(data.Dataset):
    def __init__(self, root=''):
        super(TrainDataset, self).__init__()
        self.img_files = glob(os.path.join(root,'image','*.png'))
        self.mask_files = []
        for img_path in self.img_files:
            basename = os.path.basename(img_path)
            self.mask_files.append(os.path.join(root,'mask',basename[:-4]+'_mask.png'))
            

    def __getitem__(self, index):
            img_path = self.img_files[index]
            mask_path = self.mask_files[index]
            data = cv2.imread(img_path, cv2.IMREAD_UNCHANGED)
            label = cv2.imread(mask_path, cv2.IMREAD_UNCHANGED)
            return torch.from_numpy(data).float(), torch.from_numpy(label).float()

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.img_files)

class TestDataset(data.Dataset):
    def __init__(self, root=''):
        super(TestDataset, self).__init__()
        self.img_files = glob(os.path.join(root,'image','*.png'))

    def __getitem__(self, index):
            img_path = self.img_files[index]
            data = cv2.imread(img_path, cv2.IMREAD_UNCHANGED)
            return torch.from_numpy(data).float()

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.img_files)

import torch
import torch.nn as nn
import torch.nn.functional as F


class CNNSEG(nn.Module): # Define your model
    def __init__(self):
        super(CNNSEG, self).__init__()
        # fill in the constructor for your model here

        self.relu = nn.ReLU()

        #Define first Convolutional layer
        self.conv1_1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=1, out_channels=16, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.conv1_2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=16, out_channels=16, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.batchnorm1 = nn.BatchNorm2d(16)

        #Define second Convolutional layer
        self.conv2_1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=16, out_channels=32, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.conv2_2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=32,out_channels=32, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.batchnorm2 = nn.BatchNorm2d(32)

        #Define third Convolutional layer
        self.conv3_1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=32, out_channels=64, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.conv3_2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=64, out_channels=64, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.conv3_3 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=64, out_channels=64, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.batchnorm3 = nn.BatchNorm2d(64)

        #Define fourth Convolutional layer
        self.conv4_1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=64, out_channels=128, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.conv4_2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=128, out_channels=128, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.conv4_3 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=128, out_channels=128, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.batchnorm4 = nn.BatchNorm2d(128)

        #Define fifth Convolutional layer
        self.conv5_1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=128, out_channels=256, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.conv5_2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=256, out_channels=256, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.conv5_3 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=256, out_channels=256, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.batchnorm5 = nn.BatchNorm2d(256)

        #Define the transition layer. Only change the channel
        self.trans1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=256, out_channels=128, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.trans2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=128, out_channels=64, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.trans3 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=64, out_channels=4, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.trans4 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=128, out_channels=128, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)
        self.trans5 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=64, out_channels=64, kernel_size=(3,3), padding=1, stride=1)

        #Define the maxpool layer, reduce the size to one half
        self.maxpool = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=(2,2), stride=2)

        #Define the upsample layer
        self.upsample_2x = nn.UpsamplingBilinear2d(scale_factor=2)
        self.upsample_8x = nn.UpsamplingBilinear2d(scale_factor=8)

        
        
        
        
        

    def VGG16part(self, x):

        # VGG Block1, input(4,1,96,96) -> output(4,16,48,48)
        x1 = self.relu(self.batchnorm1(self.conv1_1(x))) #(4,1,96,96) -> (4,16,96,96)
        x1 = self.relu(self.batchnorm1(self.conv1_2(x1))) #(4,16,96,96)
        x1 = self.maxpool(x1) #(4,16,48,48)

        # VGG Block2, input(4,16,48,48) -> output(4,32,24,24)
        x2 = self.relu(self.batchnorm2(self.conv2_1(x1))) #(4,32,48,48)
        x2 = self.relu(self.batchnorm2(self.conv2_2(x2))) #(4,32,48,48)
        x2 = self.maxpool(x2) #(4,32,24,24)

        # VGG Block3, input(4,32,24,24) -> output(4,64,12,12)
        x3 = self.relu(self.batchnorm3(self.conv3_1(x2))) #(4,64,24,24)
        x3 = self.relu(self.batchnorm3(self.conv3_2(x3))) #(4,64,24,24)
        x3 = self.relu(self.batchnorm3(self.conv3_3(x3))) #(4,64,24,24)
        x3 = self.maxpool(x3) #(4,64,12,12)

        # VGG Block4, input(4,64,12,12) -> output(4,128,6,6)
        x4 = self.relu(self.batchnorm4(self.conv4_1(x3))) #(4,128,12,12)
        x4 = self.relu(self.batchnorm4(self.conv4_2(x4))) #(4,128,12,12)
        x4 = self.relu(self.batchnorm4(self.conv4_3(x4))) #(4,128,12,12)
        x4 = self.maxpool(x4) #(4,128,6,6)

        # VGG Block5, input(4,128,6,6) -> output(4,256,3,3)
        x5 = self.relu(self.batchnorm5(self.conv5_1(x4))) #(4,256,6,6)
        x5 = self.relu(self.batchnorm5(self.conv5_2(x5))) #(4,256,6,6)
        x5 = self.relu(self.batchnorm5(self.conv5_3(x5))) #(4,256,6,6)
        x5 = self.maxpool(x5) #(4,256,3,3)

        return x1,x2,x3,x4,x5

    def forward(self, x):
        # fill in the forward function for your model here

        # get the output of VGG16 part
        x1,x2,x3,x4,x5 = self.VGG16part(x)

        # Upsampleing layer1, at a factor of 2  input(4,256,3,3)->(4,128,6,6)+(4,128,6,6)->output(4,128,6,6)
        x6 = self.trans1(x5) #(4,128,3,3)
        x6 = self.upsample_2x(x6) #(4,128,6,6)
        x7 = x6 + x4 #(4,128,6,6)
        x7 = self.relu(self.batchnorm4(self.trans4(x7)))

        # Upsampleing layers2, at a factor of 2  input(4,128,6,6)->(4,64,12,12)+(4,45,12,12)->output(4,64,12,12)
        x8 = self.trans2(x7) #(4,64,6,6)
        x8 = self.upsample_2x(x8) #(4,64,12,12)
        x9 = x3 + x8 #(4,64,12,12)
        x9 = self.relu(self.batchnorm3(self.trans5(x9)))

        # Upsampleing layers2, at a factor of 8  input(4,64,12,12)->(4,4,96,96)+(4,4,96,96)->output(4,4,96,96)
        out = self.trans3(x9) #(4,4,12,12)
        out = self.upsample_8x(out) #(4,4,96,96)

        return out

import torch
import torch.nn as nn
import torch.nn.functional as F



class SeparableConv2d(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self,in_channels,out_channels,kernel_size=1,stride=1,padding=0,dilation=1,bias=False):
        super(SeparableConv2d,self).__init__()

        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels,in_channels,kernel_size,stride,padding,dilation,groups=in_channels,bias=bias)
        self.pointwise = nn.Conv2d(in_channels,out_channels,kernel_size=1,stride=1,padding=0,dilation=1,groups=1,bias=bias)

    def forward(self,x):
        x = self.conv1(x)
        x = self.pointwise(x)
        return x
# Change this Xception implementation to Aligned Xception https://github.com/hoya012/pytorch-Xception/blob/master/Xception_pytorch.ipynb
class Xception(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_channel):
        super(Xception, self).__init__()

        # Entry Flow
        self.entry_flow_1 = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Conv2d(input_channel, 16, kernel_size=3, stride=2, padding=1, bias=False), # 48*48 output stride = 2
            nn.BatchNorm2d(16),
            nn.ReLU(True),

            nn.Conv2d(16, 32, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(32),
            nn.ReLU(True)
        )

        self.entry_flow_2 = nn.Sequential(
            SeparableConv2d(32, 64, 3, 1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(64),
            nn.ReLU(True),

            SeparableConv2d(64, 64, 3, 1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(64),
            nn.ReLU(True),

            # Improve for deeplab v3+
            # Depthwise Convolution
            SeparableConv2d(64, 64, 3, 2, padding=1),# 24*24 output stride = 4
            nn.BatchNorm2d(64),
            nn.ReLU(True),

        )

        self.entry_flow_2_residual = nn.Conv2d(32, 64, kernel_size=1, stride=2, padding=0) # 24*24 output stride = 4

        self.entry_flow_3 = nn.Sequential(

            SeparableConv2d(64, 128, 3, 1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(128),
            nn.ReLU(True),

            SeparableConv2d(128, 128, 3, 1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(128),
            nn.ReLU(True),

            # Improve for deeplab v3+
            # Depthwise Convolution
            SeparableConv2d(128, 128, 3, 2, padding=1),# 12*12 output stride = 8
            nn.BatchNorm2d(128),
            nn.ReLU(True),

        )

        self.entry_flow_3_residual = nn.Conv2d(64, 128, kernel_size=1, stride=2, padding=0) # 12*12 output stride = 8

        self.entry_flow_4 = nn.Sequential(

            SeparableConv2d(128, 256, 3, 1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(256),
            nn.ReLU(True),

            SeparableConv2d(256, 256, 3, 1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(256),
            nn.ReLU(True),

            # Improve for deeplab v3+
            # Atrous Convolution
            nn.Conv2d(in_channels=256,out_channels=256,kernel_size=3,stride=2,padding=2,dilation=2), # 6*6 output stride = 16 with atrous
            nn.BatchNorm2d(256),
            nn.ReLU(True),

        )

        self.entry_flow_4_residual = nn.Conv2d(128, 256, kernel_size=1, stride=2, padding=0) # 6*6 output stride = 16

        # Middle Flow
        self.middle_flow = nn.Sequential(

            SeparableConv2d(256, 256, 3, 1, padding=1), # keep size 6*6
            nn.BatchNorm2d(256),
            nn.ReLU(True),

            SeparableConv2d(256, 256, 3, 1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(256),
            nn.ReLU(True),

            SeparableConv2d(256, 256, 3, 1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(256),
            nn.ReLU(True),
        )

        # Exit Flow
        self.exit_flow_1 = nn.Sequential(
            SeparableConv2d(256, 256, 3, 1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(256),
            nn.ReLU(True),

            SeparableConv2d(256, 512, 3, 1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(512),
            nn.ReLU(True),

            # Atrous Convolution
            nn.Conv2d(in_channels=512,out_channels=512,kernel_size=3,stride=1,padding=4,dilation=4), # 6*6 output stride = 16 with atrous
            nn.BatchNorm2d(512),
            nn.ReLU(True),

        )
        self.exit_flow_1_residual = nn.Conv2d(256, 512, kernel_size=1, stride=1, padding=0) # 6*6 output stride = 16

        self.exit_flow_2 = nn.Sequential(
            SeparableConv2d(512, 768, 3, 1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(768),
            nn.ReLU(True),

            # Improve for deeplab v3+
            # Depthwise Convolution
            SeparableConv2d(768, 768, 3, 1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(768),
            nn.ReLU(True),

            SeparableConv2d(768, 1024, 3, 1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(1024),
            nn.ReLU(True)
        )


    def forward(self, x):
        entry_out1 = self.entry_flow_1(x)
        entry_out2 = self.entry_flow_2(entry_out1) + self.entry_flow_2_residual(entry_out1)
        entry_out3 = self.entry_flow_3(entry_out2) + self.entry_flow_3_residual(entry_out2)
        entry_out = self.entry_flow_4(entry_out3) + self.entry_flow_4_residual(entry_out3)


        middle_out = self.middle_flow(entry_out) + entry_out

        for i in range(7):
            middle_out = self.middle_flow(middle_out) + middle_out

        exit_out1 = self.exit_flow_1(middle_out) + self.exit_flow_1_residual(middle_out)
        exit_out2 = self.exit_flow_2(exit_out1)

        output = exit_out2

        return output,entry_out2

class ASPP(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, inplanes, planes, rate):
        super(ASPP, self).__init__()
        self.atrous_convolution = nn.Conv2d(inplanes, planes, kernel_size=3,
                        stride=1, padding=rate, dilation=rate)
        self.batch_norm = nn.BatchNorm2d(planes)
        self.relu = nn.ReLU(True)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.atrous_convolution(x)
        x = self.batch_norm(x)
        x = self.relu(x)

        return x

class CNNSEG(nn.Module): # Define your model
    def __init__(self):
        super(CNNSEG, self).__init__()
        # Step 1 feature extractor
        self.feature_extractor = Xception(input_channel=1)
        self.output_stride = 16

        # Step 2 ASPP
        #ASPP
        rates = [6, 12, 18]
        self.aspp1 = nn.Conv2d(1024, 256, kernel_size=1)
        self.aspp1_bn = nn.BatchNorm2d(256)

        self.aspp2 = ASPP(1024, 256, rate=rates[0])
        self.aspp3 = ASPP(1024, 256, rate=rates[1])
        self.aspp4 = ASPP(1024, 256, rate=rates[2])

        self.global_avg_pool = nn.Sequential(nn.AdaptiveAvgPool2d((1, 1)),
                        nn.Conv2d(1024, 256, 1, stride=1),
                        nn.BatchNorm2d(256),
                        nn.ReLU(True)
                        )
        self.relu = nn.ReLU(True)
        self.dropout_0_5 = nn.Dropout2d(0.5)

        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(1280, 256, 1)
        self.bn1 = nn.BatchNorm2d(256)

        # Decoder Part
        #channel reduction to 32.
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(64, 32, 1)
        self.bn2 = nn.BatchNorm2d(32)


        self.last_conv = nn.Sequential(nn.Conv2d(288, 256, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=1),
                        nn.BatchNorm2d(256),
                        nn.ReLU(True),
                        nn.Conv2d(256, 256, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=1),
                        nn.BatchNorm2d(256),
                        nn.ReLU(True),
                        nn.Dropout2d(0.1),
                        nn.Conv2d(256, 4, kernel_size=1, stride=1))

    def forward(self, x):

        # Encoder Part
        x,low_level_features = self.feature_extractor(x)

        x1 = self.aspp1(x)
        x1 = self.aspp1_bn(x1)

        x2 = self.aspp2(x)
        x3 = self.aspp3(x)
        x4 = self.aspp4(x)
        x5 = self.global_avg_pool(x)

        x5 = F.interpolate(x5, size=x4.size()[2:], mode='bilinear', align_corners=True)



        # Decoder Part
        x = torch.cat((x1, x2, x3, x4, x5), dim=1)
        x = self.conv1(x)
        x = self.bn1(x)
        x = self.dropout_0_5(x)

        x = F.interpolate(x, scale_factor= self.output_stride//4, mode='bilinear', align_corners=True)

        low_level_features = self.conv2(low_level_features)
        low_level_features = self.bn2(low_level_features)

        x = torch.cat((x, low_level_features), dim=1)
        x = self.last_conv(x)

        x = F.interpolate(x, scale_factor= self.output_stride//(self.output_stride//4), mode='bilinear', align_corners=True)

        return x

model = CNNSEG().to(device) # We can now create a model using your defined segmentation model

def sum_tensor(inp, axes, keepdim=False):
    # copy from: https://github.com/MIC-DKFZ/nnUNet/blob/master/nnunet/utilities/tensor_utilities.py
    axes = np.unique(axes).astype(int)
    for ax in sorted(axes, reverse=True):
        inp = inp.sum(int(ax))
    return inp

def get_results(net_output, gt, axes, mask=None):
    # Shape of output and target
    shape_x = net_output.shape
    shape_y = gt.shape

    with torch.no_grad():
        if len(shape_x) != len(shape_y):
            gt = gt.view((shape_y[0], 1, *shape_y[1:]))
        
        # Check if one hot encoding, if not encode
        if all([i == j for i, j in zip(net_output.shape, gt.shape)]):
            y_onehot = gt
        else:
            gt = gt.long()
            y_onehot = torch.zeros(shape_x)
            if net_output.device.type == "cuda":
                y_onehot = y_onehot.cuda(net_output.device.index)
            y_onehot.scatter_(1, gt, 1)

    tp = net_output * y_onehot
    fp = net_output * (1 - y_onehot)
    fn = (1 - net_output) * y_onehot

    # Sum tensor values
    tp = sum_tensor(tp, axes)
    fp = sum_tensor(fp, axes)
    fn = sum_tensor(fn, axes)

    return tp, fp, fn

class SoftDiceLoss(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self,smooth=0.1):
        super(SoftDiceLoss, self).__init__()
        self.smooth = smooth

    def forward(self, x, y, loss_mask=None):
        shp_x = x.shape
        axes = list(range(2, len(shp_x)))

        true_p, false_p, false_n = get_results(x, y, axes)
        dc = (2 * true_p + self.smooth) / (2 * true_p + false_p + false_n + self.smooth)
        dc = dc.mean() 

        return 1-dc

class CrossDice(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, dice=None, cross = None, weight=None, size_average=True):
        super(CrossDice, self).__init__()
        weights = [0.5, 1.0, 1.0, 1.0]
        class_weights = torch.FloatTensor(weights).to(device)
        self.dice = SoftDiceLoss()
        self.cross = nn.CrossEntropyLoss(weight = class_weights)
    
    def forward(self, inputs, targets):
        cross_loss = self.cross.forward(inputs, targets)
        dice_loss = self.dice.forward(inputs, targets)
        
        comb_loss = cross_loss*dice_loss
        
        return comb_loss

3.2 Define a Evaluation function to measure the performance - Dice Score¶

***Code is copied form tutorial***

In [11]:
def categorical_dice(mask1, mask2, label_class=1):
    """
    Dice score of a specified class between two volumes of label masks.
    (classes are encoded but by label class number not one-hot )
    Note: stacks of 2D slices are considered volumes.

    Args:
        mask1: N label masks, numpy array shaped (H, W, N)
        mask2: N label masks, numpy array shaped (H, W, N)
        label_class: the class over which to calculate dice scores

    Returns:
        volume_dice
    """
    mask1_pos = (mask1 == label_class).astype(np.float32)
    mask2_pos = (mask2 == label_class).astype(np.float32)
    dice = 2 * np.sum(mask1_pos * mask2_pos) / (np.sum(mask1_pos) + np.sum(mask2_pos))
    return dice

import numpy as np
import os
import cv2

def rle_encoding(x):
    '''
    *** Credit to https://www.kaggle.com/rakhlin/fast-run-length-encoding-python ***
    x: numpy array of shape (height, width), 1 - mask, 0 - background
    Returns run length as list
    '''
    dots = np.where(x.T.flatten() == 1)[0]
    run_lengths = []
    prev = -2
    for b in dots:
        if (b > prev + 1): run_lengths.extend((b + 1, 0))
        run_lengths[-1] += 1
        prev = b
    return run_lengths


def submission_converter(mask_directory, path_to_save):
    writer = open(os.path.join(path_to_save, "submission.csv"), 'w')
    writer.write('id,encoding\n')

    files = os.listdir(mask_directory)

    for file in files:
        name = file[:-4]
        mask = cv2.imread(os.path.join(mask_directory, file), cv2.IMREAD_UNCHANGED)

        mask1 = (mask == 1)
        mask2 = (mask == 2)
        mask3 = (mask == 3)

        encoded_mask1 = rle_encoding(mask1)
        encoded_mask1 = ' '.join(str(e) for e in encoded_mask1)
        encoded_mask2 = rle_encoding(mask2)
        encoded_mask2 = ' '.join(str(e) for e in encoded_mask2)
        encoded_mask3 = rle_encoding(mask3)
        encoded_mask3 = ' '.join(str(e) for e in encoded_mask3)

        writer.write(name + '1,' + encoded_mask1 + "\n")
        writer.write(name + '2,' + encoded_mask2 + "\n")
        writer.write(name + '3,' + encoded_mask3 + "\n")

    writer.close()

from torch.utils.data import DataLoader
import numpy as np
import time

def training(train_epochs=20):
    data_path = './new_data/train'
    if(torch.cuda.is_available):
        num_workers = 0
    else:
        num_workers = 4
    batch_size = 4
    train_set = TrainDataset(data_path)
    training_data_loader = DataLoader(dataset=train_set, num_workers=num_workers, batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True)

    model.train()

    epochs = train_epochs

    for epoch in range(epochs):
        # Fetch images and labels.  
        train_loss = 0
        train_acc = 0
        start_time = time.time()
        i=0
        for iteration, sample in enumerate(training_data_loader):
            img, mask = sample

            # show_image_mask(img[0,...].squeeze(), mask[0,...].squeeze()) #visualise all data in training set
            # plt.pause(1)
            
            # Write your FORWARD below
            # Note: Input image to your model and ouput the predicted mask and Your predicted mask should have 4 channels
            # img = img.unsqueeze(1).to(device)
            img = img.view(4,1,96,96).to(device)
            # mask = mask.unsqueeze(1).to(device)
            # mask = mask.view(4,1,96,96).to(device)
            mask = mask.to(device)
            mask = mask.type(torch.long)

            # model.zero_grad()
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            out = model.forward(img)
            out = F.log_softmax(out)
            
            # Then write your BACKWARD & OPTIMIZE below
            # Note: Compute Loss and Optimize
            loss = Loss(out, mask)
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()
            train_loss += loss.data.item()

            pred = out.max(1)[1].squeeze().cpu().data.numpy()

            score = 0
            for i in range(4):
                score += categorical_dice(np.array(pred), np.array(mask.cpu()), i)
            # score = categorical_dice(np.array(pred), np.array(mask.cpu()), 0)
            # score += categorical_dice(np.array(pred), np.array(mask.cpu()), 1)
            # score += categorical_dice(np.array(pred), np.array(mask.cpu()), 2)
            # score += categorical_dice(np.array(pred), np.array(mask.cpu()), 3)

            train_acc += score/4
        
        print("epoch: ", epoch, "| loss: ", train_loss/len(training_data_loader), "| training time: ", time.time()-start_time, "| accuracy: ", train_acc/len(training_data_loader))
